04451nam a22006495i 9780271081847DE-B159720211027022714.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211027t20212018pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710818477 a10.1515/97802710818472doi  a(DE-B1597)584133  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aE164b.H71513 2018eb 7aHIS0370502bisacsh04a917.304/332231 aHoffmann, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aPosthumous America :bLiterary Reinventions of America at the End of the Eighteenth Century /cBenjamin Hoffmann. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (256 p.) :b3 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: New World Paradoxes -- t1 Saint-John de Crèvecoeur and Nostalgia for Colonial America -- t2 Lezay-Marnésia and Nostalgia for the American Golden Age -- t3 Chateaubriand and Nostalgia for French America -- tConclusion: America, a Mobile Sign -- tAppendix -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBenjamin Hoffmann's Posthumous America examines the literary idealization of a lost American past in the works of French writers of the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. For writers such as John Hector St. John de Crèvecœur and Claude-François de Lezay-Marnésia, America was never more potent as a driving ideal than in its loss. Examining the paradoxical American paradise depicted in Crèvecœur's Lettres d'un cultivateur américain (1784); the "uchronotopia"-the imaginary perfect society set in America and based on what France might have become without the Revolution-of Lezay-Marnésia's Lettres écrites des rives de l'Ohio (1792); and the political and nationalistic motivations behind François-René Chateaubriand's idealization of America in Voyage en Amérique (1827) and Mémoires d'outre-tombe (1850), Hoffmann shows how the authors' liberties with the truth helped create the idealized and nostalgic representation of America that dominated the collective European consciousness of their times. From a historical perspective, Posthumous America works to determine when exactly these writers stopped transcribing what they actually observed in America and started giving imaginary accounts of their experiences.A vital contribution to transatlantic studies, this detailed exploration of French perspectives on the colonial era, the War of Independence, and the birth of the American Republic sheds new light on the French fascination with America. Posthumous America will be invaluable for historians, political scientists, and specialists of literature whose scholarship looks at America through European eyes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Okt 2021) 0aTravelers' writings, FrenchxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Modern / 18th Century.2bisacsh1 aSingerman, Alan J.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311074522140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271081847zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271081847423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780271081847/original  a978-3-11-074522-1  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK